"""
================================================================================
BVAR PCE INFLATION FORECASTING -- Minnesota prior, monthly, ragged-edge nowcast
================================================================================
Bayesian VAR for forecasting US PCE inflation from an ALIGNED monthly panel
(each row = reference month; a cell is populated only once that statistic has
actually been released for that month). Because CPI (mid-month release) always
precedes PCE (end-of-month release), the last row(s) of the panel are "ragged":
CPI, PPI, market data etc. are filled while PCE is still NaN. The script
detects this ragged edge automatically and produces a CONDITIONAL nowcast of
the next PCE print given everything already published -- no look-ahead bias,
and re-running the script after each new release updates everything.

Methodology (with citations):
  * Minnesota prior via dummy observations:
        Litterman (1986); Doan, Litterman & Sims (1984);
        Banbura, Giannone & Reichlin (2010, JAE) -- "large BVAR" construction.
    Own-lag prior mean delta_i (0 for growth-rate/differenced series, which
    is the standard setting for inflation rates; ~0.9 for persistent levels),
    overall tightness lambda, harmonic lag decay l^d, scales sigma_i from
    univariate AR residual std devs.
  * Sum-of-coefficients and dummy-initial-observation priors:
        Doan et al. (1984); Sims (1993); Sims & Zha (1998).
  * Hyperparameters chosen by maximizing the closed-form marginal likelihood
    of the conjugate Normal-Inverse-Wishart model:
        Giannone, Lenza & Primiceri (2015, REStat).
  * Conjugate NIW posterior -> exact Monte Carlo (no MCMC):
        Sigma ~ IW, B|Sigma ~ Matrix-Normal; density forecasts carry both
        parameter and shock uncertainty (Karlsson 2013, Handbook ch. 15).
  * COVID outliers via observation dummies with a loose prior, in the spirit
    of Lenza & Primiceri (2022, JAE).
  * NOWCAST = exact conditional forecasting ("hard conditions") a la
        Waggoner & Zha (1999, REStat), with parameter uncertainty:
    for every posterior draw (B, Sigma) the stacked h-step-ahead predictive
    distribution is Gaussian, so we condition analytically on every value
    already released at the ragged edge (CPI first!) and simulate the
    remaining elements -- this is the standard research setup for
    CPI-conditioned PCE nowcasts (cf. Knotek & Zaman 2017, JMCB, "Nowcasting
    U.S. headline and core inflation").
  * Out-of-sample: recursive pseudo-real-time backtest vs AR(p), the
    Atkeson & Ohanian (2001) random-walk benchmark, and the historical mean;
    the CONDITIONAL nowcast itself is backtested (each origin conditions on
    that month's CPI-block exactly as it would in real time), so you can see
    how much the CPI print buys you at h=1. RMSE ratios + interval coverage.
    (On inflation forecast evaluation generally: Faust & Wright 2013,
    Handbook of Economic Forecasting; Stock & Watson 2007, JMCB.)

USAGE
-----
1) Edit CONFIG (file path, column names, transforms).
2) python bvar_pce_inflation.py              (your data)
   python bvar_pce_inflation.py --selftest   (synthetic panel w/ ragged edge)
Outputs (fan chart, nowcast density, OOS PNGs, CSVs, summary) -> output_dir.

EXPECTED DATA LAYOUT
--------------------
One date column plus one column per series. Two layouts are supported
(config "data_frequency"):
  * "monthly"      : one row per reference month, values placed in their
                     reference month, NaN until released.  <-- your setup
  * "daily_asknown": daily rows, each series forward-filled with its latest
                     published value (like the GDP script). Trailing months
                     are then NOT ragged, so the automatic nowcast
                     conditioning will not trigger; prefer "monthly".
  * "auto"         : guess from the median spacing of the date index.

IMPORTANT -- ALIGNMENT: with an aligned monthly panel every value already
sits in its reference month, so "target_release_shift_m" should stay 0.
Only use a nonzero shift if you feed a dragged/as-known panel where the
latest published PCE refers to a previous month.

UPDATING: just refresh the Excel file and re-run. Whatever is filled in for
months where PCE is still missing is picked up automatically and folded into
the nowcast + fan chart. You can also inject values that are not in the file
yet via CONFIG["manual_conditions"] (in TRANSFORMED units).
================================================================================
"""

